org.gearvrf

Class GVRSwitch

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.gearvrf.GVRHybridObject
      • org.gearvrf.GVRComponent
        • org.gearvrf.GVRBehavior
          • org.gearvrf.GVRSwitch
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    GVRDrawFrameListener

    public class GVRSwitch
extends GVRBehavior
    A switch node is a component that will display only one child of a scene object. It can be used to select from among several versions of an object. When the GVRSwitch component is attached to a GVRSceneObject it sets all but one of the scene object's children to be invisible. You can control which child is visible by setting the switch index.
    See Also:

      • getSwitchIndex

        public int getSwitchIndex()
        Gets the current switch index that selects what object to display. This value indexes the children of the scene object which owns this component.
        Returns:
        0 based switch index

      • setSwitchIndex

        public void setSwitchIndex(int index)
        Sets the current switch index that selects what object to display. This value is a zero-based index into the children of the scene object which owns this component. If it is out of range, none of the children will be shown.
        Parameters:
        index - 0 based index into children of owner.
        See Also:
        GVRSceneObject.getChildByIndex(int)

      • selectByName

        public void selectByName(java.lang.String childName)
        Sets the current switch index based on object name. This function finds the child of the scene object this component is attached to and sets the switch index to reference it so this is the object that will be displayed. If it is out of range, none of the children will be shown.
        Parameters:
        childName - name of child to select
        See Also:
        GVRSceneObject.getChildByIndex(int)

      • onDrawFrame

        public void onDrawFrame(float frameTime)
        Selects the child object to be displayed based on the switch index. If the switch index does not reference a valid child, nothing is displayed. It is not called if this behavior is not attached to a GVRSceneObject.
        Specified by:
        onDrawFrame in interface GVRDrawFrameListener
        Overrides:
        onDrawFrame in class GVRBehavior
        Parameters:
        frameTime - Seconds since the previous frame - see GVRContext.getFrameTime()
